reserve f for (PartFunc of ( REAL ),( REAL ));
theorem
((x0 in ( dom f ) & f is_continuous_in x0) implies (( abs f ) is_continuous_in x0 & ( - f ) is_continuous_in x0))
proof
assume A1: x0 in ( dom f );
assume A2: f is_continuous_in x0;
now
let s1;
assume that
A3: ( rng s1 ) c= ( dom ( abs f ) )
and
A4: (s1 is  convergent & ( lim s1 ) = x0);
A5: ( rng s1 ) c= ( dom f ) by A3,VALUED_1:def 11;
then A6: ( f . x0 ) = ( lim ( f /* s1 ) ) by A2,A4,CKB1:def 1;
A7: ( f /* s1 ) is  convergent by A2,A4,A5,CKB1:def 1;
then ( abs ( f /* s1 ) ) is  convergent by SEQ_4:13;
hence ( ( abs f ) /* s1 ) is  convergent by A5,RFUNCT_2:10;
thus ( ( abs f ) . x0 ) = ( abs ( f . x0 ) ) by VALUED_1:18
.= ( lim ( abs ( f /* s1 ) ) ) by A7,A6,SEQ_4:14
.= ( lim ( ( abs f ) /* s1 ) ) by A5,RFUNCT_2:10;
end;
hence ( abs f ) is_continuous_in x0 by CKB1:def 1;
thus thesis by A1,A2,CKB9:1;
end;
